Package veve.datastructures.trees

Class NTreeNode<K extends java.lang.Comparable<K>,​V>

  • java.lang.Object
    • veve.datastructures.trees.NTreeNode<K,​V>
  • Type Parameters:
    K - The type of the nodes id. Must implement Comparable.
    V - The type of the value property of the node.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Comparable<NTreeNode<K,​V>>, java.lang.Iterable<NTreeNode<K,​V>>
    public class NTreeNode<K extends java.lang.Comparable<K>,​V>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Iterable<NTreeNode<K,​V>>, java.lang.Comparable<NTreeNode<K,​V>>
    A tree node that has an id, a value and zero or more child nodes. Children of a node cannot have the same id. The id in a NTreeNode cannot be null but the value can be null. The node is also required to have a reference to a NTree which is the owner of the node but the node is not necessarily part of the tree who is its owner.

    A node can also be considered as the root of a subtree or node hierarchy even if it does not not formally form part of an NTree.

    All methods from NTreeNode that modify the node or subtree will update the indexes of the NTree that owns this node if the node is formally part of the trhat tree so the indexes are automatically kept in sync with the node changes.

    The methods of this class that use functional interface arguments convert the lambda function passed to another lambda function that prevents NullPointerException from breaking the execution and instead make the lambda function return null or false or not execute if it is a Consumer. If a NullPointerException is thrown for a Predicate or BiPredicate argument the result of executing the lambda function would be false. If the parameter is of type Function then the result of the lambda function would be null.

    Note that no method accepts null values as arguments except setValue(Object)

    The NearestCommonAncestorTool class can be used to find the nearest common ancestor between two nodes in a tree plus having other methods to get all nodes between the path between them and the their common ancestor.

    This class is not thread safe.

      Returns an integer which based on weather it is negative, zero or positive determines if this node is less than, equal to or greater than the other node.
      Null values are considered less than to non null values and comparison between two nulls returns 0.
      If this.id.compareTo(other.id) returns 0 (equal) and the class of the value property implements Comparable then the value properties are also compared.

      • replaceSingleNodeWith

        public NTreeNode<K,​V> replaceSingleNodeWith​(NTreeNode<K,​V> other)
        Replaces this node in a node hierarchy or tree with another node without replacing the node's descendants. The node passed will not be changed and instead a clone of it will be used.
        Parameters:
        other - the node to replace this node
        Returns:
        this node if replaced or null if it did not replace this node. Reasons for not replacing this node can be one of the following:
        • The node to replace this node is this node.
        • This node is not a root of a NTree and it's parent is null.
        • This node has a sibling node that has the same id as the replacement node.

      • removeAndParentAdoptsGrandChildren

        public java.util.List<NTreeNode<K,​V>> removeAndParentAdoptsGrandChildren​(java.util.function.BiPredicate<NTreeNode<K,​V>,​NTreeNode<K,​V>> bipredicate)
        Removes this node from a tree or node hierarchy and it's parent adopts it's children (it's parent grandchildren).
        Parameters:
        bipredicate - a BiPredicate that if evaluates to true then siblings of this node that have the same id as the adopted children are replaced by the children with the same id. If it evaluates to false then the children are removed and the uncle with the same id remains. The first argument of the BiPredicate is for the node's child and the second for the node's sibling.
        Returns:
        a list containing this node if it was removed plus any node that was replaced, if any or null if it was not removed

        Returns:
        a list containing the node that was removed plus any node that was replaced, if any or null if it was not removed

        Removes this node from a tree or node hierarchy and it's parent adopts it's children (it's parent grandchildren). If a child of this node has the same id as a sibling of node and this nodereplacesDuplicates argument is true the sibling is removed, but if replacesDuplicates argument is false the child is removed.
